This study used SPSS 25.0 statistical software for data processing. First, the Kolmogorov-Smirnov test was used to check the normality of the data. Data that followed a normal distribution were presented as mean ± standard deviation, while data that did not follow a normal distribution were presented as median (interquartile range, IQR). Categorical data were presented as frequency (percentage). Data from the two groups of patients at preoperative (T0), immediate postoperative (T1), and one-year postoperative (T2) were analyzed. For continuous variables that followed a normal distribution, an independent samples t-test was used. For data that did not follow a normal distribution, the Mann-Whitney U test was applied. Categorical data were analyzed using the chi-square test or Fisher’s exact test. A \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\:P$$\end{document} value < 0.05 was considered statistically significant.

A total of 10 patients who met the inclusion criteria were enrolled in this study, involving 55 teeth. All patients completed the surgical procedure and subsequent follow-up, and no adverse reactions such as infection or material loss occurred post-surgery. Based on the bone grafting technique used, patients were divided into two groups: the digital guided bone grafting (GBG) group and the Control group. Table 1 presents a comparison of the basic demographic characteristics between the two groups. No significant differences were observed in terms of gender, age, height, weight, or BMI (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
