In addition to bone regeneration, the improvement of soft tissue is another important consideration following PAOO surgery [35–38]. In this study, while the primary focus was on bone regeneration, improvements in soft tissue were also observed. Changes in gingival biotype and KW were noted in both groups. As demonstrated in the existing literature, there is a robust correlation between PD and the presence of plaque biofilms in the gingival region. Furthermore, there is a positive correlation between KW and the capacity of periodontal tissues to resist inflammatory stimuli [36]. Consequently, enhancement of keratinized gingiva has been shown to augment the resistance of periodontal tissues to inflammation, a development that is particularly advantageous for orthodontic patients afflicted with concomitant oral diseases, such as periodontitis. In this study, it was found that, at one year postoperatively, the mean increase in keratinized gingival width in the GBG group was 1.76 mm (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\:P$$\end{document} < 0.001), which was significantly higher than that of the Control group. Moreover, the proportion of thick gingival biotype in the GBG group reached 100% postoperatively, indicating a certain degree of soft tissue improvement. This enhancement may be ascribed to the interplay between bone regeneration and soft tissue. Current research suggests that thick gingival biotype may provide a more favorable osteogenic environment for guided bone regeneration (GBR) by offering a thicker bone foundation, stronger soft tissue support, and a lower risk of complications [39]. Interestingly, the GBG group in this study had a significantly lower proportion of thick gingival biotype at baseline compared to the Control group. However, our results showed that the GBG group appeared to achieve greater soft tissue regeneration at the one-year follow-up, which may be attributed to the enhanced bone regeneration facilitated by the use of digital bone graft guides. This improvement in bone regeneration likely contributed to the shift toward a thicker gingival biotype, allowing the GBG group to gain more benefits in terms of soft tissue outcomes. Improved bone regeneration provides more stable support for the soft tissue, reducing soft tissue recession. The substantial increase in bone regeneration undoubtedly laid a solid foundation for soft tissue enhancement [40]. In turn, soft tissue regeneration may further promote bone regeneration through mechanisms such as improved blood supply, reduced mechanical disturbance, and enhanced barrier function.
